%I A396727 #33 Jun 23 2026 09:23:01
%S A396727 0,1,8,477,50128,507558725,9438928992,102621927493714223,
%T A396727 44970047782779123636416,28977228869837770693955029581,
%U A396727 22954528746372225790890814301786200,82247296290822181760722510222907593219117851139,26543913505488885745557595072893853027066426494480432
%N A396727 a(n) is the numerator of the expected number of turns in the parallelized coupon anticollector's problem, also referred to as the generalized Yahtzee problem.
%C A396727 The parallelized coupon anticollector's problem consists of rolling n dice, each with n faces labeled from 1 to n, until all dice display face n. After each roll, the dice that show face n are set aside and are not rolled again. a(n) denotes the numerator of the expected number of turns, E(n).
%C A396727 An analogous scenario involves cereal boxes, each containing one of n equally probable coupon types, where the objective is to collect n coupons of a specific type. On the first day, n boxes are purchased; on subsequent days, all boxes lacking the desired coupon type are exchanged. In this context, a(n) represents the numerator of the expected waiting time, E(n).
%C A396727 Equivalently, E(n) is the expected maximum of n geometric random variables, each with expectation n.
%C A396727 If the geometric distribution is replaced with the exponential, E(n) becomes n*H(n) [Eisenberg] where H(n) = A001008(n)/A002805(n). This also corresponds to the original coupon collector's problem, which determines the expected time to collect every coupon type when acquiring one coupon per day.
%H A396727 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A396727/b396727.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..43</a>
%H A396727 Bennett Eisenberg, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.spl.2007.05.011">On the expectation of the maximum of IID geometric random variables</a>, Statistics & Probability Letters 27 (2008), pp. 135-143.
%H A396727 Mathematics StackExchange, <a href="https://math.stackexchange.com/q/26167">Expectation of the maximum of n i.i.d. geometric random variables</a>, 2011.
%F A396727 E(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} C(n, k) * (-1)^(k-1) / (1-(1-1/n)^k).
%F A396727 E(n) = Sum_{j>=0} 1 - (1-(1-1/n)^j)^n. (j-th summand is chance of undergoing turn j.)
%F A396727 Sum_{k=1..n} C(n, k) * Sum_{j>=0} (1-(1-1/n)^j)^(n-k) * (1-1/n)^(k*j). ((k, j)-th summand is chance of undergoing turn j with k coupons remaining uncollected.)
%F A396727 E(n) ~ H(n)/log(1 + 1/(n-1)) + 1/2 where H(n) = A001008/A002805. The error of this approximation converges exponentially well (see StackExchange answer).
%e A396727 Fractions begin: 0, 1, 8/3, 477/95, 50128/6475, 507558725/47291409, 9438928992/677218157, 102621927493714223/5924958775655777, ...
%e A396727 .
%e A396727 Let state s consist of s remaining dice. In the n = 3 case, the transition probabilities, placed in a matrix (with transitions to 0 omitted), give:
%e A396727   1->i: (2/3,  0 ,   0 )
%e A396727   2->i: (4/9, 4/9,   0 )
%e A396727   3->i: (2/9, 4/9, 8/27).
%e A396727 Then (I - M)^-1 is:
%e A396727   (   3  ,    0  ,   0  )
%e A396727   ( 12/5 ,   9/5 ,   0  )
%e A396727   (234/95, 108/95, 27/19).
%e A396727 Note that (I - M)^-1_{i, j} = C(i, j)*Sum_{k>=0} (1-(2/3)^k)^(i-j)*(2/3)^(k*j) is the expected number of turns spent in state j when starting from state i. So E(3) = 234/95 + 108/95 + 27/19 = 477/95.
%p A396727 A396727 := n -> local k; numer(add((-1)^k * binomial(n, k) / (((n - 1) / n)^k - 1), k = 1..n)): seq(A396727(n), n = 0..12);  # _Peter Luschny_, Jun 18 2026
%t A396727 A396727[n_] := Numerator[Sum[Binomial[n, k]*(-1)^k/(((n - 1)/n)^k - 1), {k, n}]];
%t A396727 Array[A396727, 15, 0] (* _Paolo Xausa_, Jun 20 2026 *)
%o A396727 (Python)
%o A396727 from fractions import Fraction as frac
%o A396727 from math import comb
%o A396727 A396727 = lambda n: sum(comb(n, k) * frac((-1)**k,frac(n - 1, n)**k - 1) for k in range(1, n + 1)).numerator
%o A396727 print(list(map(A396727,range(20))))
%Y A396727 Cf. A001008/A002805: harmonic numbers.
%Y A396727 Cf. A096617/A027611: expected time to get all coupons, where only one can be bought/exchanged per turn.
%Y A396727 Cf. A392624/A392625: expected time to get all coupons, by exchanging all but one copy of each already-occurred type.
%K A396727 nonn,frac
